Backtracking is a powerful algorithmic technique used to solve problems recursively by trying all possible solutions and reverting back to previous states when a solution is not found. One classic problem that can be solved using backtracking is the N-Queens puzzle, which involves placing N queens on an NxN chessboard such that no queen attacks any other queen.

To solve this problem using backtracking, we start by considering the empty board as our starting state. We then recursively try all possible placements of a queen on the board, checking if the current placement violates any constraints (e.g., placing two queens in the same row or column). If a solution is found, we return it. Otherwise, we continue trying all possible placements until a valid solution is found or we reach the end of the recursion tree.

When implementing backtracking algorithms like this one, it's essential to have a clear understanding of the problem domain and the necessary data structures to solve it. In the case of the N-Queens puzzle, we need to consider both rows and columns as the queen can be placed horizontally or vertically on each square. We also need to keep track of which squares are occupied by queens to avoid placing two queens in the same row or column.

To solve this problem using backtracking, we start by creating an NxN array to represent the chessboard and initializing it with empty spaces. Then, we recursively try all possible placements of a queen on the board, checking if the current placement violates any constraints. If a solution is found, we return it. Otherwise, we continue trying all possible placements until a valid solution is found or we reach the end of the recursion tree.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to solve this problem using backtracking in Java:
```java
public class NQueens {
  public static boolean[][] board; // Array representing the chessboard
  public static int N = 8; // Size of the chessboard (default is 8x8)

  public static void solve() {
    board = new boolean[N][N];
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
      for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
        board[i][j] = false;
      }
    }

    solve(0, 0);
  }

  public static void solve(int row, int col) {
    if (row == N) { // Base case: all queens are placed
      printBoard();
      return;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
      for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
        if (!isValid(row, col)) { // If the current placement violates any constraint
          continue;
        }

        board[row][col] = true; // Place a queen on the board
        solve(row + 1, col); // Recursive call to try placing the next queen
        board[row][col] = false; // Reset the current square to empty
      }
    }
  }

  public static boolean isValid(int row, int col) {
    for (int i = 0; i < row; i++) {
      if (board[i][col]) { // Check if a queen is already placed in the same column
        return false;
      }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < col; i++) {
      if (board[row][i]) { // Check if a queen is already placed in the same row
        return false;
      }
    }

    for (int i = Math.max(row - 1, 0); i < N; i++) {
      for (int j = Math.max(col - 1, 0); j < N; j++) {
        if (board[i][j]) { // Check if a queen is already placed in the same diagonal
          return false;
        }
      }
    }

    return true; // No violations found, current placement is valid
  }

  public static void printBoard() {
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
      for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
        if (board[i][j]) { // Print a queen on the board
          System.out.print("Q ");
        } else {
          System.out.print("_ ");
        }
      }
      System.out.println();
    }
  }
}
```
