 Recursion is a programming technique where the solution to a problem depends on solutions to smaller instances of the same problem, whereas iteration involves repeating a set of instructions until some condition is met.
In recursive algorithms, each call to the function creates a new stack frame and executes its code independently from other calls. The recursion continues until it reaches a base case that does not require further recursion. In contrast, iterative algorithms use loops to execute a set of instructions repeatedly until a certain condition is satisfied.
The advantage of using recursion over iteration can be seen in cases where the problem has an underlying structure that naturally lends itself to breaking down into smaller subproblems. For example, sorting a list of integers by recursively dividing it into halves and comparing each pair of elements until the list is fully sorted.
On the other hand, iteration might offer more flexibility when solving problems with dynamic or unpredictable structures or where there are multiple ways to handle certain cases. It can also be easier to implement for certain algorithms that do not have a clear structure for recursion.

