```cpp
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n == 0)
        return 1; // Base case: 0! = 1

    int result = n * factorial(n - 1); // Recursive call to calculate n!

    return result;
}
```

This function simply calls itself with a smaller argument until the base case is reached. The recursion ends when `n` equals zero, at which point it returns the value of one.

Here's an example of an iterative version called `factorial_iterative`, that calculates the factorial using a loop:

```cpp
int factorial_iterative(int n) {
    int result = 1;

    for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i)
        result *= i;

    return result;
}
```

