  ["Q",".","."]
]
```

This code provides the solution to placing `n` queens on an `n x n` chessboard without any two queens attacking each other. The backtracking method ensures that we find a valid placement of all queens on the board.

### Conclusion:

The N-Queens problem is a great example for teaching backtracking as it involves checking constraints and recursively solving subproblems while maintaining a solution space. This approach is versatile and can be extended to many similar problems involving placing items or agents in different grids or planes.
